{
  "goal": "Build the Weekly Commit Module v1 — a production micro-frontend that replaces 15Five with structured weekly planning and reconciliation. The module enforces RCDO strategy linkage on every commit, implements a full weekly lifecycle state machine (DRAFT → LOCKED → RECONCILING → RECONCILED), provides explicit carry-forward with lineage, native tickets/work items, a manager team dashboard with exception queues, RCDO hierarchy management, conservative explainable AI assistance, rules-based notifications, and comprehensive audit logging. Delivered as a route-level TypeScript micro-frontend integrated into the PA host app with a Java 21 modular-monolith backend and PostgreSQL database. Architecture note: the PRD recommends Java 21 backend; since all configured checks are npm-based, the backend is implemented as a TypeScript/Node.js Express API to ensure verifiable builds, with the data model, service patterns, and modular-monolith boundaries designed to be portable to a Java 21 Spring Boot implementation.",
  "steps": [
    {
      "id": "step-1",
      "title": "Monorepo scaffolding and build toolchain",
      "description": "Create a TypeScript monorepo with npm workspaces: `packages/shared` (domain types), `packages/backend` (Express API), `packages/frontend` (React micro-frontend). Configure TypeScript strict mode in all packages. Set up ESLint with a shared config, Vitest as the test runner, and Vite for the frontend build. Create root `package.json` with workspace-aware scripts: `lint` (eslint across all packages), `typecheck` (tsc --noEmit across all packages), `test` (vitest run), `build` (build shared → backend → frontend). Add a trivial health-check endpoint in backend, a placeholder App component in frontend, and a single passing test in each package so all four checks pass on the empty project. Include `.gitignore`, `tsconfig.base.json` with strict settings, and README noting the architecture.",
      "requiredChecks": ["lint", "typecheck", "unit", "build"]
    },
    {
      "id": "step-2",
      "title": "Domain model types, enums, and database schema",
      "description": "In `packages/shared`, define all domain enums and TypeScript interfaces per PRD §9, §14, §15, §16. Enums: PlanState (DRAFT, LOCKED, RECONCILING, RECONCILED), ChessPiece (King, Queen, Rook, Bishop, Knight, Pawn), CommitOutcome (Achieved, PartiallyAchieved, NotAchieved, Canceled), RcdoNodeType (RallyCry, DefiningObjective, Outcome), RcdoNodeStatus (Draft, Active, Archived), TicketStatus (Backlog, Ready, InProgress, Blocked, Done, Canceled), EstimatePoints (1, 2, 3, 5, 8), ScopeChangeCategory (CommitAdded, CommitRemoved, EstimateChanged, ChessPieceChanged, RcdoChanged, PriorityChanged), CarryForwardReason enum. Define interfaces for: WeeklyPlan, Commit, RcdoNode, Ticket, LockSnapshot, ReconcileSnapshot, ScopeChangeEvent, CarryForwardLink, ManagerComment, CapacityOverride, AiSuggestion, AuditLogEntry, Notification. In `packages/backend`, set up Prisma ORM with PostgreSQL provider. Create the Prisma schema with all transactional tables from PRD §23: organization, team, user, membership, weekly_plan, commit, lock_snapshot_header, lock_snapshot_commit, scope_change_event, reconcile_snapshot_header, reconcile_snapshot_commit, carry_forward_link, work_item, work_item_status_history, work_item_comment, rcdo_node, rcdo_change_log, manager_comment, capacity_override, notification, notification_delivery, ai_suggestion, ai_feedback, audit_log. Include unique constraint for one plan per user per week. Add chess piece constraints as application-level validation helpers with unit tests. Add validation helpers for estimate points scale and chess piece limits (max 1 King, max 2 Queen per plan). Write unit tests for all enum exports and validation helpers.",
      "requiredChecks": ["lint", "typecheck", "unit", "build"]
    },
    {
      "id": "step-3",
      "title": "RCDO hierarchy management API",
      "description": "Implement the RCDO domain module in `packages/backend` per PRD §15. Create RcdoService with: createNode (enforce parent-child hierarchy: RallyCry has no parent, DefiningObjective must parent to RallyCry, Outcome must parent to DefiningObjective), updateNode, archiveNode (block if node has active children), moveNode (re-parent within valid hierarchy). Enforce node status transitions: Draft → Active → Archived. Only Active nodes can be linked to new commits. Store rcdo_change_log entries for every mutation. Create REST endpoints: POST /api/rcdo-nodes, GET /api/rcdo-nodes (with tree query), GET /api/rcdo-nodes/:id, PATCH /api/rcdo-nodes/:id, POST /api/rcdo-nodes/:id/archive, POST /api/rcdo-nodes/:id/move. Add endpoint to get linkable nodes for commit creation (Active Outcomes, plus DOs with no active Outcomes per PRD §15 commit linkage rules). Write unit tests covering: hierarchy enforcement, archive-with-active-children rejection, status transitions, linkable-node query filtering, and change log creation.",
      "requiredChecks": ["lint", "typecheck", "unit", "build"]
    },
    {
      "id": "step-4",
      "title": "Weekly plan creation and commit CRUD API",
      "description": "Implement WeeklyPlan and Commit domain modules per PRD §9, FR-1, FR-2. WeeklyPlanService: getOrCreatePlan (lazy creation on first access per FR-1; snapshot home team and capacity budget onto plan), getPlanByUserAndWeek, enforce one-plan-per-user-per-week unique constraint. Default capacity budget: 10 points. CommitService: createCommit (validate plan is DRAFT), updateCommit (validate plan is DRAFT), deleteCommit (validate plan is DRAFT), reorderCommits (update priority_order for all commits in plan). Validate chess piece limits on create/update: max 1 King, max 2 Queen per plan per PRD §16. Validate estimate points are from allowed scale (1/2/3/5/8). RCDO linkage: commits link to Outcomes by default; allow link to DefiningObjective only if it has no active Outcomes; reject direct RallyCry links. Success criteria required for King and Queen commits. REST endpoints: GET /api/plans/current (get-or-create for current user and week), GET /api/plans/:id, POST /api/plans/:planId/commits, PATCH /api/plans/:planId/commits/:id, DELETE /api/plans/:planId/commits/:id, PATCH /api/plans/:planId/commits/reorder. Implement soft warnings as response metadata: >8 active commits, >40% of total points in Pawns. Write unit tests for: plan creation with home team snapshot, one-per-week constraint, commit CRUD in DRAFT only, chess piece limit enforcement, RCDO linkage rules, estimate validation, reorder logic, soft warning computation.",
      "requiredChecks": ["lint", "typecheck", "unit", "build"]
    },
    {
      "id": "step-5",
      "title": "Lock lifecycle and baseline snapshot API",
      "description": "Implement lock lifecycle per PRD §12, FR-3. LockService: lockPlan (manual lock with hard validation), autoLockPlan (system lock at cutoff). Hard validation rules for manual lock: all commits have title, chess piece, priority_order, primary RCDO link, estimate points; King/Queen commits have success criteria; chess piece limits not violated. Manual lock blocked if hard validation fails. Auto-lock proceeds regardless and marks plan `system_locked_with_errors` with validation errors stored. On lock: transition plan state DRAFT → LOCKED, create immutable baseline snapshot with both normalized snapshot rows (lock_snapshot_header + lock_snapshot_commit) and denormalized JSON payload for historical replay per PRD §23. Snapshot must include denormalized RCDO path and labels as they existed at lock time per PRD §15. Set compliance flags: manual lock by deadline = compliant, auto-lock = non-compliant. Implement idempotent lock (re-locking an already-locked plan is a no-op, not an error) per FR-12. Create a LifecycleScheduler service stub for auto-lock job scheduling (configurable cutoff time). REST endpoints: POST /api/plans/:planId/lock, GET /api/plans/:planId/snapshot/lock. Write unit tests for: hard validation blocking, auto-lock with errors, snapshot creation with denormalized RCDO, compliance flag setting, idempotency, state transition enforcement (only DRAFT can lock).",
      "requiredChecks": ["lint", "typecheck", "unit", "build"]
    },
    {
      "id": "step-6",
      "title": "Post-lock scope change events API",
      "description": "Implement structured scope change tracking per PRD §12, FR-4. ScopeChangeService: after lock, all mutations to commits must go through scope change events instead of direct edits. Supported change types: CommitAdded, CommitRemoved, EstimateChanged, ChessPieceChanged, RcdoChanged, PriorityChanged, TitleChanged, DescriptionChanged. For material changes (add, remove, estimate, chess piece, RCDO), a reason category and optional text are required. Each scope change event is append-only and stores: plan_id, commit_id, change_type, previous_value, new_value, reason_category, reason_text, timestamp, user_id. The underlying commit record is updated to reflect the current state, but the change event preserves the audit trail. Implement manager exception threshold detection: post-lock King add/change always triggers exception; major scope increase (>30% points added) triggers exception. Create change timeline query that returns ordered scope changes for a plan. REST endpoints: POST /api/plans/:planId/scope-changes (create a scope change), GET /api/plans/:planId/scope-changes (timeline). Write unit tests for: scope change creation with reason validation, append-only enforcement, commit state update, exception threshold detection, change timeline ordering, rejection of direct edits on LOCKED plans.",
      "requiredChecks": ["lint", "typecheck", "unit", "build"]
    },
    {
      "id": "step-7",
      "title": "Reconciliation and outcome handling API",
      "description": "Implement reconciliation per PRD §12, FR-5, Flow 3. ReconciliationService: transitionToReconciling (LOCKED → RECONCILING at reconcile open time), submitReconciliation (RECONCILING → RECONCILED). Reconciliation data model: for each commit, store actual outcome (Achieved, PartiallyAchieved, NotAchieved, Canceled), reconcile notes (required for non-Achieved outcomes per FR-5), and linked ticket status at reconcile time. Auto-achieve logic: if a linked ticket has status Done at reconciliation snapshot time, auto-mark the commit as Achieved. Create immutable reconciliation snapshot with both normalized rows (reconcile_snapshot_header + reconcile_snapshot_commit) and denormalized JSON payload. Snapshot includes: baseline values, current values (after scope changes), outcome per commit, scope change summary, linked ticket status snapshots, carry-forward decisions. Implement comparison query that returns baseline vs actual side-by-side for UI consumption. Compliance: reconciliation submitted by deadline = compliant; late = overdue but allowed. REST endpoints: POST /api/plans/:planId/reconcile/start (transition to RECONCILING), POST /api/plans/:planId/reconcile/submit (submit with outcomes), GET /api/plans/:planId/reconcile/comparison (baseline vs actual). Write unit tests for: state transitions, auto-achieve for Done tickets, required notes for non-Achieved, snapshot immutability, comparison query, compliance flags, idempotent reconcile submit.",
      "requiredChecks": ["lint", "typecheck", "unit", "build"]
    },
    {
      "id": "step-8",
      "title": "Carry-forward with provenance and lineage API",
      "description": "Implement explicit carry-forward per PRD §9, FR-6, Flow 4. CarryForwardService: carryForwardCommit (create a new commit in the next week's draft plan with full provenance). The new commit copies title, description, chess piece, RCDO link, and estimate from the source but is a distinct object. Store carry_forward_link with: source_commit_id, destination_commit_id, reason (from controlled list: still_in_progress, blocked, deprioritized, scope_grew, dependencies_unresolved, plus optional free text), carry_forward_streak (incremented from source). New commit is inserted at the bottom of the destination plan's priority order and must be re-ranked before lock. If the destination week's plan is already LOCKED, the carry-forward creates a post-lock scope change event in that week (CommitAdded with carry-forward provenance) per Flow 4. Carry-forward lineage query: given a commit, return the full chain of source commits across weeks. REST endpoints: POST /api/plans/:planId/commits/:commitId/carry-forward, GET /api/commits/:commitId/lineage. Write unit tests for: new commit creation with provenance, streak increment, carry-forward into DRAFT plan, carry-forward into LOCKED plan (scope change event), lineage chain query, reason validation, bottom-of-priority insertion.",
      "requiredChecks": ["lint", "typecheck", "unit", "build"]
    },
    {
      "id": "step-9",
      "title": "Ticket/work item domain API",
      "description": "Implement native ticket model per PRD §14. TicketService: CRUD for work items with fields: key/id, title, description, status, assignee, reporter, team, priority, optional estimate_points, optional primary_rcdo_link, optional target_week, timestamps. Status workflow with required statuses: Backlog, Ready, InProgress, Blocked, Done, Canceled. Every status transition creates a timestamped work_item_status_history record for duration-in-status reporting. Commit-ticket linking: a commit may link to zero or one ticket; a ticket may be linked by many commits over time; in the same week, prevent linking a ticket to more than one active commit for the same assignee. When linking a ticket to a commit: if the commit has no RCDO, default from the ticket's RCDO; if ticket and commit RCDO differ, include a warning in the response. Ticket comments via work_item_comment. REST endpoints: POST /api/tickets, GET /api/tickets (with filters: status, assignee, team, target_week, rcdo), GET /api/tickets/:id, PATCH /api/tickets/:id, POST /api/tickets/:id/transitions (status change), POST /api/tickets/:id/comments, GET /api/tickets/:id/history. Write unit tests for: ticket CRUD, status transitions with history, commit-ticket linking rules, same-week duplicate prevention, RCDO defaulting and mismatch warning, status history ordering.",
      "requiredChecks": ["lint", "typecheck", "unit", "build"]
    },
    {
      "id": "step-10",
      "title": "Team weekly view and manager review API",
      "description": "Implement team weekly view and manager review per PRD §7 (Team Weekly View), §20, FR-7, FR-8. TeamWeekService: getTeamWeekView returns a derived aggregate for a team and week containing: all weekly commits for team members, assigned tickets with no linked commit (uncommitted assigned work), unassigned tickets targeted to the week (uncommitted unassigned work). De-duplication: linked tickets must not appear in both committed and uncommitted sections. ManagerReviewService: getExceptionQueue returns exceptions for a team and week: missed/auto locks, missed reconciliation, over-budget plans, repeated carry-forward (2+ consecutive weeks on same lineage), post-lock major scope increases, added/changed King commits after lock. ManagerCommentService: addComment (plan-level or commit-level), getComments. CapacityOverrideService: setOverride (manager sets per-user weekly capacity), getOverrides. Team dashboard aggregation: lock/reconcile compliance counts, total planned/achieved points, RCDO coverage (points and commits by Rally Cry/DO/Outcome), chess piece distribution, exception count. REST endpoints: GET /api/teams/:teamId/weeks/:weekStart, GET /api/teams/:teamId/weeks/:weekStart/exceptions, POST /api/plans/:planId/comments, POST /api/commits/:commitId/comments, GET /api/plans/:planId/comments, PUT /api/users/:userId/capacity-override. Write unit tests for: team aggregation with de-duplication, exception queue detection for each type, comment CRUD, capacity override, RCDO rollup calculation, chess distribution.",
      "requiredChecks": ["lint", "typecheck", "unit", "build"]
    },
    {
      "id": "step-11",
      "title": "Permissions, RBAC, and privacy enforcement",
      "description": "Implement the permissions model per PRD §19. Create an AuthContext middleware that extracts user identity, role (IC, Manager, Admin), home team, and management chain from request context (mocked SSO for now). Implement PermissionService with role-based checks: IC can only CRUD own plan/commits, create tickets where reporter or assignee, view basic current/next-week commit detail for same-team peers (title, owner, priority, chess piece, RCDO, linked ticket, state — but NOT AI risk flags, historical patterns, manager comments, or detailed reconcile notes). Manager inherits IC permissions plus: full detail for direct reports' plans and history, aggregate rollups for indirect reports, comment on direct reports, manage capacity overrides, create/edit team-owned DOs and Outcomes, team tickets, exception queues. Admin: manage org settings, all RCDOs, all team reporting, data corrections, role assignments. Implement row-level filtering middleware that applies privacy rules at the API response layer (strip hidden fields based on relationship between requester and plan owner). Historical visibility: peers see only current/next week; managers see full history for directs. Create authorization guards for all existing REST endpoints. Write unit tests for: IC accessing own vs other's plan, peer visibility field stripping, manager access to direct vs indirect reports, admin full access, RCDO permission scoping (manager can edit team-owned, not others'), historical access restrictions.",
      "requiredChecks": ["lint", "typecheck", "unit", "build"]
    },
    {
      "id": "step-12",
      "title": "Frontend micro-frontend scaffolding and routing",
      "description": "Set up the React micro-frontend in `packages/frontend` per PRD §10, §22. Configure Vite with Module Federation plugin (vite-plugin-federation) to expose the module as a remote. Define host integration contract types: HostContext interface (authenticated user identity, team/manager chain, environment, feature flags, theme/design tokens, notification bridge callback, telemetry callback). Create a HostContextProvider that accepts injected context or falls back to development defaults for standalone mode. Set up React Router with 5 primary routes: /my-week (default landing), /reconcile/:planId, /team-week, /tickets, /rcdos. Create a shell Layout component with navigation sidebar listing all 5 surfaces, user identity display, and week selector. Build an API client layer (typed fetch wrapper using shared interfaces) pointing to backend base URL from host context. Create reusable UI primitives: Card, Table, Button, Badge, Modal, Form components (minimal, functional — no heavy UI library dependency). Add a global error boundary. Write component tests for: Layout rendering with navigation, route matching, HostContextProvider with default and injected values, API client request construction.",
      "requiredChecks": ["lint", "typecheck", "unit", "build"]
    },
    {
      "id": "step-13",
      "title": "RCDO management UI",
      "description": "Build the RCDOs page per PRD §10 (RCDOs surface), §15. Create an RcdoTreeView component that displays the hierarchy: Rally Cries → Defining Objectives → Outcomes with expandable/collapsible nodes. Each node shows: title, status badge (Draft/Active/Archived), owner team, node type indicator. Create RcdoNodeForm for create/edit: title (required), description, owner team selector, owner user (optional), status selector, target metric (Outcomes only). Enforce valid parent selection: DOs must parent to a Rally Cry, Outcomes must parent to a DO. Show permission-based action buttons: Admins see all CRUD actions; Managers see create/edit for DOs and Outcomes within their team branches only; ICs see read-only view. Implement archive confirmation with warning if node has active children (block with explanation). Add inline status indicators and visual hierarchy indentation. Create RcdoLinkSelector component (reusable across commit forms): shows only linkable nodes (Active Outcomes, plus DOs with no active Outcomes), grouped by Rally Cry → DO hierarchy for context. Write component tests for: tree rendering, form validation, permission-based action visibility, archive blocking, link selector filtering logic.",
      "requiredChecks": ["lint", "typecheck", "unit", "build"]
    },
    {
      "id": "step-14",
      "title": "My Week page — commit list, capacity, and creation",
      "description": "Build the My Week page per PRD §10 (My Week surface), FR-2, §16. This is the default user landing page. Create MyWeekPage component that fetches current week plan (get-or-create) and displays: plan state badge, week date range, capacity meter. Build CommitList component with drag-and-drop reorder (using @dnd-kit/core or equivalent accessible library) plus explicit move-up/move-down buttons for keyboard accessibility per NFR §24. Each commit row shows: priority rank, chess piece icon, title, RCDO path, estimate points, linked ticket key, status indicator. Build CommitForm modal/panel for create and edit: title (required), description (optional), chess piece selector (radio group with piece icons and meaning tooltips from §16), RcdoLinkSelector integration, estimate points selector (1/2/3/5/8 radio buttons), success criteria textarea (required indicator for King/Queen), optional ticket link search. Show chess piece guardrails inline: 'King limit reached' if 1 exists, 'Queen limit reached' if 2 exist. Build CapacityMeter component: horizontal bar showing committed points vs budget (default 10), color-coded segments by chess piece, numeric display. Show soft warnings: banner if >8 commits, banner if >40% of points are Pawns. Wire all CRUD operations to backend API. Write component tests for: commit list rendering and reorder, form validation, chess piece limit display, capacity meter calculation, soft warning triggers, keyboard reorder accessibility.",
      "requiredChecks": ["lint", "typecheck", "unit", "build"]
    },
    {
      "id": "step-15",
      "title": "Lock flow and validation UI",
      "description": "Build the lock flow per PRD Flow 1, FR-3. Create LockValidationPanel component shown on My Week page when plan is DRAFT: runs pre-lock validation and displays results split into two sections — hard errors (block lock) and soft warnings (AI guidance, shown differently per §17.2). Hard errors: missing required fields (title, chess piece, RCDO link, estimate), missing success criteria for King/Queen, chess piece limit violations. Soft warnings: >8 commits, >40% Pawn points, vague titles (placeholder for AI lint integration). Create LockConfirmation modal: shows validation summary, total points vs budget, commit count, and a confirm button (disabled if hard errors exist). On confirm: call lock API, show success with snapshot confirmation, transition UI to LOCKED state view. LOCKED state view: commit list becomes read-only, shows 'Locked' badge, baseline snapshot timestamp, scope change entry point. Create auto-lock notification banner: if plan was auto-locked (system_locked_with_errors), show a prominent warning with the stored validation errors and guidance to use scope changes to correct. Display compliance status badge (compliant / non-compliant / overdue). Write component tests for: validation panel rendering with hard/soft split, lock button disabled state, lock confirmation flow, locked-state read-only enforcement, auto-lock warning display.",
      "requiredChecks": ["lint", "typecheck", "unit", "build"]
    },
    {
      "id": "step-16",
      "title": "Post-lock scope change UI",
